une and the rise and fall of impressionism raised serious doubts about the power of collectivism in art and life. Fantin-Latour's monumental group portraits, and related works by his friends and colleagues from the 1850s through the 1880s, represent varied visions of collective identity and test the limits of association as both a social and an artistic pursuit. By examining the bonds and frictions that animated their social circles, Fantin-Latour and his cohorts developed a new pictorial language for the modern group: one of fragmentation, exclusion, and willful withdrawal into interior space that nonetheless presented individuality as radically relational.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aArt and societyzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aArtistszFrancevPortraits. 0aGroup identity in art. 0aPortrait painting, Frenchy19th century. 0aPortraits, GroupzFrance. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh  aAcademic art.  aAlfred Sisley.  aAllegory.  aAlois Riegl.  aAlphonse Legros.  aAmbroise Vollard.  aAnomie.  aAntoine Guillemet.  aApotheosis.  aArt criticism.  aArthur Rimbaud.  aBad Painting.  aBanality (sculpture series).  aBohemian style.  aBoredom.  aBourgeoisie.  aCamille Pissarro.  aCaricature.  aCarle Vernet.  aChampfleury.  aCharles Baudelaire.  aCubism.  aDegenerate art.  aEasel.  aEdgar Allan Poe.  aEdgar Degas.  aEdmund Gosse.  aEmmanuel Chabrier.  aEnfant terrible.  aExclusion.  aFarce.  aFine art.  aFrans Hals.  aFrench art.  aGenre painting.  aGeorg Simmel.  aGustave Caillebotte.  aGustave Courbet.  aGustave Moreau.  aHedda Sterne.  aHenri Fantin-Latour.  aHistory painting.  aHomage (arts).  aHorace Vernet.  aHyperbole.  aImpressionism.  aJacques Derrida.  aJacques-Louis David.  a